---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';

const faq = [
  {
    question: "What is Redis Vector Search?",
    answer: "Redis Vector Search is a feature of Redis Stack (and Redis Cloud) that adds vector similarity search capabilities to Redis. It uses the RediSearch module under the hood, allowing you to create HNSW or FLAT (brute-force) vector indexes on Redis Hash or JSON documents and run KNN (K-Nearest Neighbor) queries. Because Redis is an in-memory data structure store, vector search results return in sub-millisecond latency."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the difference between HNSW and FLAT index types in Redis?",
    answer: "FLAT performs brute-force exact nearest neighbor search — it scans every vector and guarantees 100% recall accuracy, but search time is O(n). Use FLAT for small collections (<100K vectors) or when 100% accuracy is required. HNSW is an approximate index that trades a small amount of recall accuracy for dramatically faster search at scale. HNSW is the recommended choice for production workloads with >100K vectors."
  },
  {
    question: "What is redisvl (Redis Vector Library)?",
    answer: "redisvl (redis-py-vector) is the official high-level Python library for Redis Vector Search. It provides a declarative schema definition, automatic index management, document ingestion with embedding functions, and a clean search API. It abstracts away the raw FT.CREATE and FT.SEARCH commands, making it much easier to build RAG pipelines on Redis. Install with: pip install redisvl"
  },
  {
    question: "Can I filter by metadata alongside vector search in Redis?",
    answer: "Yes. When you define a vector index with FT.CREATE, you can also index scalar fields (TEXT, TAG, NUMERIC, GEO) in the same schema. At search time, you combine a KNN vector query with any RediSearch filter expression — for example: (@category:{ai} @year:[2024 +inf])=>[KNN 5 @embedding $query_vec]. This pre-filters candidates before KNN scoring."
  },
  {
    question: "When should I use Redis Vector Search vs a dedicated vector database?",
    answer: "Redis Vector Search excels for real-time, low-latency applications where you already use Redis for caching, session management, or pub/sub — adding vector search avoids a separate service. It is ideal for <10M vectors with sub-millisecond latency requirements. For billion-scale workloads, dedicated vector databases (Milvus, Qdrant) provide better scaling, more index types, and features like quantization. Redis cannot cost-effectively hold hundreds of millions of vectors entirely in RAM."
  },
  {
    question: "Does Redis Vector Search work with Redis Cloud?",
    answer: "Yes. Redis Cloud (Managed Redis) includes RediSearch and vector search capabilities in all paid tiers. You can also use Redis Stack locally (docker run -d redis/redis-stack) or on Redis Enterprise. The redisvl library and raw FT.CREATE commands work identically across all deployment options — just change the connection URL."
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Redis Vector Search: Real-Time Similarity Search Guide"
  description="Complete guide to Redis Vector Search — Redis Stack setup, HNSW and FLAT indexes, FT.CREATE vector field, FT.SEARCH KNN syntax, metadata filtering, redisvl Python library, and Redis vs dedicated vector DB comparison."
  tool="Redis vector search, Redis Stack, KNN search, real-time vector search, redisvl"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"WebPage","name":"Redis Vector Search: Real-Time Similarity Search Guide","url":"https://devplaybook.cc/tools/redis-vector-search","description":"Complete Redis Vector Search guide — HNSW/FLAT indexes, FT.CREATE, KNN queries, metadata filtering, and redisvl Python library."})} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Redis Vector Search: Real-Time Similarity Search Guide</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">Redis Vector Search brings sub-millisecond vector similarity search to your existing Redis infrastructure. Built into Redis Stack via the RediSearch module, it supports HNSW and FLAT indexes, metadata filtering alongside KNN queries, and the high-level redisvl Python library — ideal for real-time AI features where latency is critical.</p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Sub-millisecond latency</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> HNSW &amp; FLAT indexes</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> KNN + metadata filter</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> redisvl high-level SDK</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Redis Cloud managed option</span>
  </div>

  <ToolPageCta />

  <!-- Setup and FT.CREATE -->
  <section class="mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Setup: Redis Stack &amp; FT.CREATE Vector Index</h2>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">Run Redis Stack with Docker and create a vector index using the raw Redis commands.</p>
    <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-sm font-mono overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code class="text-green-400"># Run Redis Stack locally (includes RediSearch + vector search)
# docker run -d -p 6379:6379 redis/redis-stack

pip install redis openai redisvl

import redis
import struct
import json

r = redis.Redis(host="localhost", port=6379, decode_responses=False)

# Create HNSW vector index on Hash documents
# Fields: embedding (vector), category (tag), year (numeric), content (text)
r.execute_command(
    "FT.CREATE", "idx:articles",
    "ON", "HASH",
    "PREFIX", "1", "article:",
    "SCHEMA",
        "content",   "TEXT",
        "category",  "TAG",
        "year",      "NUMERIC", "SORTABLE",
        "embedding", "VECTOR", "HNSW", "6",
            "TYPE",      "FLOAT32",
            "DIM",       "1536",
            "DISTANCE_METRIC", "COSINE"
)

# FLAT (brute-force) index for small datasets / exact search
r.execute_command(
    "FT.CREATE", "idx:small_docs",
    "ON", "HASH",
    "PREFIX", "1", "doc:",
    "SCHEMA",
        "embedding", "VECTOR", "FLAT", "6",
            "TYPE", "FLOAT32",
            "DIM",  "1536",
            "DISTANCE_METRIC", "COSINE"
)</code></pre>
  </section>

  <!-- Insert and FT.SEARCH -->
  <section class="mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Insert Vectors &amp; FT.SEARCH KNN Query</h2>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">Store documents as Redis Hashes and query with FT.SEARCH KNN syntax including metadata filters.</p>
    <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-sm font-mono overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code class="text-green-400">import openai

oa = openai.OpenAI()

def embed(text: str) -> bytes:
    vec = oa.embeddings.create(
        model="text-embedding-3-small", input=text
    ).data[0].embedding
    # Convert float list to bytes for Redis storage
    return struct.pack(f"&#123;len(vec)&#125;f", *vec)

# Insert documents as Redis Hashes
docs = [
    &#123;"id": "1", "content": "RAG systems improve LLM accuracy", "category": "ai",  "year": 2024&#125;,
    &#123;"id": "2", "content": "Redis supports real-time vector search", "category": "db", "year": 2024&#125;,
    &#123;"id": "3", "content": "HNSW index for fast ANN search",       "category": "db", "year": 2023&#125;,
]
for doc in docs:
    r.hset(f"article:&#123;doc['id']&#125;", mapping=&#123;
        "content":   doc["content"],
        "category":  doc["category"],
        "year":      doc["year"],
        "embedding": embed(doc["content"])
    &#125;)

# KNN search with metadata pre-filter
query_bytes = embed("how does retrieval augmented generation work")

# Filter: category=ai, year >= 2024, then KNN top-3
results = r.execute_command(
    "FT.SEARCH", "idx:articles",
    "(@category:&#123;ai&#125; @year:[2024 +inf])=>[KNN 3 @embedding $query_vec AS score]",
    "PARAMS", "2", "query_vec", query_bytes,
    "RETURN", "3", "content", "category", "score",
    "SORTBY", "score",
    "DIALECT", "2"
)

# Parse results (format: [count, key, [field, val, ...], ...])
count = results[0]
print(f"Found &#123;count&#125; results:")
for i in range(1, len(results), 2):
    key = results[i].decode()
    fields = dict(zip(results[i+1][::2], results[i+1][1::2]))
    print(f"  &#123;key&#125; | score=&#123;float(fields[b'score']):.4f&#125; | &#123;fields[b'content'].decode()&#125;")</code></pre>
  </section>

  <!-- redisvl High-Level API -->
  <section class="mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">redisvl: High-Level Python Library</h2>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">redisvl abstracts FT.CREATE and FT.SEARCH into a clean Pythonic API with schema definitions and embedding functions.</p>
    <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-sm font-mono overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code class="text-green-400">from redisvl.index import SearchIndex
from redisvl.query import VectorQuery
from redisvl.utils.vectorize import OpenAITextVectorizer

# Define schema
schema = &#123;
    "index": &#123;"name": "articles", "prefix": "article"&#125;,
    "fields": [
        &#123;"name": "content",   "type": "text"&#125;,
        &#123;"name": "category",  "type": "tag"&#125;,
        &#123;"name": "year",      "type": "numeric"&#125;,
        &#123;
            "name": "embedding",
            "type": "vector",
            "attrs": &#123;
                "dims": 1536,
                "distance_metric": "cosine",
                "algorithm": "hnsw",
                "datatype": "float32"
            &#125;
        &#125;
    ]
&#125;

vectorizer = OpenAITextVectorizer(model="text-embedding-3-small")

index = SearchIndex.from_dict(schema)
index.connect("redis://localhost:6379")
index.create(overwrite=True)

# Load documents — redisvl auto-generates embeddings
data = [
    &#123;"content": "RAG systems improve LLM accuracy", "category": "ai", "year": 2024&#125;,
]
embeddings = vectorizer.embed_many([d["content"] for d in data])
for d, emb in zip(data, embeddings):
    d["embedding"] = emb
index.load(data)

# Query
query_emb = vectorizer.embed("retrieval augmented generation")
query = VectorQuery(
    vector=query_emb,
    vector_field_name="embedding",
    return_fields=["content", "category", "year"],
    num_results=3,
    filter_expression="@category:&#123;ai&#125;"
)
results = index.query(query)
for r in results:
    print(r)</code></pre>
  </section>

  <!-- Comparison Table -->
  <section class="mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Redis Vector Search vs Dedicated Vector Databases</h2>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="w-full text-sm min-w-[640px]">
        <thead>
          <tr class="text-text-muted text-xs uppercase border-b border-border">
            <th class="text-left pb-3 pr-4 font-medium">Feature</th>
            <th class="text-left pb-3 pr-4 font-medium">Redis Vector</th>
            <th class="text-left pb-3 pr-4 font-medium">Pinecone</th>
            <th class="text-left pb-3 pr-4 font-medium">Qdrant</th>
            <th class="text-left pb-3 font-medium">pgvector</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="divide-y divide-border text-text-muted">
          <tr><td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium text-text">Latency</td><td class="py-3 pr-4 text-green-500">&lt;1ms (in-memory)</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">~10–50ms</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">~5–20ms</td><td class="py-3">~5–50ms</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium text-text">Practical scale</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">~10M vectors (RAM limited)</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">100M+</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">100M+</td><td class="py-3">~50M</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium text-text">Hybrid search</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">KNN + RediSearch filters</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">Limited</td><td class="py-3 pr-4 text-green-500">Sparse + dense</td><td class="py-3">Manual</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium text-text">Multi-purpose</td><td class="py-3 pr-4 text-green-500">Cache + queue + vector</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">Vector only</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">Vector only</td><td class="py-3 text-green-500">Full SQL database</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium text-text">Persistence</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">RDB + AOF</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">Managed</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">WAL + snapshots</td><td class="py-3 text-green-500">Full ACID</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium text-text">Best for</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">Real-time, low-latency, existing Redis</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">Managed cloud prod</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">High perf self-host</td><td class="py-3">SQL+vector in PG</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faq={faq} />
  <ToolPageCta currentTool="Redis Vector Search Guide" relatedTags={['ai', 'vector-database', 'embeddings', 'rag', 'redis', 'real-time']} />
</BaseLayout>
